# torch.meshgrid

`torch.meshgrid(*tensors, indexing=None)` [source]

    
Creates grids of coordinates specified by the 1D inputs in `attr`:tensors.

This is helpful when you want to visualize data over some range of inputs. See
below for a plotting example.

Given NN 1D tensors T0…TN−1T_0 \ldots T_{N-1} as inputs with corresponding
sizes S0…SN−1S_0 \ldots S_{N-1}, this creates NN N-dimensional tensors
G0…GN−1G_0 \ldots G_{N-1}, each with shape (S0,...,SN−1)(S_0, ..., S_{N-1})
where the output GiG_i is constructed by expanding TiT_i to the result shape.

Note

0D inputs are treated equivalently to 1D inputs of a single element.

Warning

`torch.meshgrid(*tensors)` currently has the same behavior as calling
`numpy.meshgrid(*arrays, indexing=’ij’)`.

In the future `torch.meshgrid` will transition to `indexing=’xy’` as the
default.

https://github.com/pytorch/pytorch/issues/50276 tracks this issue with the
goal of migrating to NumPy’s behavior.

See also

`torch.cartesian_prod()` has the same effect but it collects the data in a
tensor of vectors.

Parameters

    
  * tensors (list of Tensor) – list of scalars or 1 dimensional tensors. Scalars will be treated as tensors of size (1,)(1,) automatically
  * indexing (Optional[str]) – 
(str, optional): the indexing mode, either “xy” or “ij”, defaults to “ij”. See
warning for future changes.

If “xy” is selected, the first dimension corresponds to the cardinality of the
second input and the second dimension corresponds to the cardinality of the
first input.

If “ij” is selected, the dimensions are in the same order as the cardinality
of the inputs.

Returns

    
If the input has NN tensors of size S0…SN−1S_0 \ldots S_{N-1}, then the output
will also have NN tensors, where each tensor is of shape (S0,...,SN−1)(S_0,
..., S_{N-1}).

Return type

    
seq (sequence of Tensors)

Example:

    
    >>> x = torch.tensor([1, 2, 3])
    >>> y = torch.tensor([4, 5, 6])
    
    Observe the element-wise pairings across the grid, (1, 4),
    (1, 5), ..., (3, 6). This is the same thing as the
    cartesian product.
    >>> grid_x, grid_y = torch.meshgrid(x, y, indexing='ij')
    >>> grid_x
    tensor([[1, 1, 1],
            [2, 2, 2],
            [3, 3, 3]])
    >>> grid_y
    tensor([[4, 5, 6],
            [4, 5, 6],
            [4, 5, 6]])
    
    This correspondence can be seen when these grids are
    stacked properly.
    >>> torch.equal(torch.cat(tuple(torch.dstack([grid_x, grid_y]))),
    ...             torch.cartesian_prod(x, y))
    True
    
    `torch.meshgrid` is commonly used to produce a grid for
    plotting.
    >>> import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
    >>> xs = torch.linspace(-5, 5, steps=100)
    >>> ys = torch.linspace(-5, 5, steps=100)
    >>> x, y = torch.meshgrid(xs, ys, indexing='xy')
    >>> z = torch.sin(torch.sqrt(x * x + y * y))
    >>> ax = plt.axes(projection='3d')
    >>> ax.plot_surface(x.numpy(), y.numpy(), z.numpy())
    >>> plt.show()
